<h2> <span class="mw-headline" id="Notes_for_Week_2:_5.3._A_Change_in_Supply">Notes for Week 2: 5.3. A Change in Supply</span></h2>
<p>What if there is an increase in the price of gasoline (an input cost):</p>
<p>Demand stays the same. 
But the supply curve would shift left 
<ul><li> it is now more expensive to produce each quantity of tomato.
</li><li> It is more expensive to transport each quantity of tomato to the market. Some may not afford
</li></ul>
As a result, the market price of tomatoes would increase and the market quantity of tomatoes would decrease.
<br />•   Supply of tomatoes will change(a shortage) and Price of Tomatoes rise. Supply curve shifts to the left.
<br />•   Fewer tomatoes are produced (5 instead of 6) and those produced have higher prices (7 instead of 6)</p>
<p>Holding everything else constant, if tomatoes go through a bad freeze, the market price of tomatoes would increase and the market quantity of tomatoes would decrease.</p>
<p></p>

